3ff8c413-a9fa-46d5-8cf1-90743d756b67.description:
Will npm install a supplied package only if not already found in node_modules .
Login account must have sudo access.
Use -g to install globally.
Usage: npmInstall packagename [-g]
3ff8c413-a9fa-46d5-8cf1-90743d756b67.name: npmInstall.sh

tempArr.c:
#!/bin/bash
return_=0
# set to 0 if found
ls node_modules | grep $1 >/dev/null 2>&1 && { return_=1; }
ls /usr/lib/node_modules | grep $1 >/dev/null 2>&1 && { return_=1; }
  if [ "$return_" -eq 1 ]; then
    echo Found
  else
    echo Not found
    sudo npm install $1 $2 --save#!/bin/bash
    sleep 3
  fi
echo done

call createNewJSON.sh file [text to append]
Eg.
createNewJSON.sh /tmp/my.json '{}'
463949ca-9c9d-478a-b6d2-b0ac1376c1b8.name: createNewJSON.sh

tempArr.c:
#!/bin/sh

file=$1

if [ ! -e "$file" ] ; then
    touch "$file"
    echo $2 >> $file
fi

if [ ! -w "$file" ] ; then
    echo cannot write to $file
    exit 1
fi

Build and execute acme-client to retrieve cert, key & ca from letsencrypt. This will allow encrypted and ca verified https communication.
https://www.npmjs.com/package/acme-client. 
Only challenge type 'http-01' is implemented.

Change

.

Ensure this server has http port 80 open and publicly reachable via  <%a.hostName%>  and not redirecting when building. 
3 files are generated;
/home/%systemUser%/.ssl/%hostName%.key  
/home/%systemUser%/.ssl/%hostName%.cert
/home/%systemUser%/.ssl/%hostName%.csr 

After the files are generated you can enable https and redirect to https

b247e208-8a34-4eed-b0d8-608de71aade0.name: mount S3 bucket on amazon-linux EC2
b247e208-8a34-4eed-b0d8-608de71aade0.script:
#install amazon-linux-extras and s3fs-fuse if /etc/fuse.con does not exist
if [ ! -f /etc/fuse.conf ] ; then sudo amazon-linux-extras install -y epel ; sudo yum install -y -q s3fs-fuse; sudo bash -c 'echo "user_allow_other" >> /etc/fuse.conf' ; fi

mkdir <%c.mountPoint%> 

#try to mount
s3fs <%c.bucketName%> <%c.mountPoint%> -o iam_role=<%c.iam_role%> -o allow_other -o url="<%c.url%>"

#display  'Failed to check IAM role name' each time it is shown in last 500 llines of system log messages
sudo tail -500  /var/log/messages | grep 'Failed to check IAM role name'

#list the mount if it exists
mount | grep 's3fs'

ops.insert:
Provides a simple service to get jason data from a data store.
Returns a row or all rows. 
Call service with 'id=#' to get all rows. Call with 'id=[id]' to get a specific row.
Eg: 
http://myNode/ezGet&id=#
   This will return all rows
http://myNode/ezGet&id=123
  This will return only row where id=123

What is ezStack Blog?
Zouder Blowbat
Sun Jul 27 2020

ezStack Blog is a blogging platform that can be designed an deployed with ezStack builder.


For more information on blogs see this extract from Wikipedia;

A blog (a truncation of "weblog")[1] is a discussion or informational website published on the World Wide Web consisting of discrete, often informal diary-style text entries (posts). Posts are typically displayed in reverse chronological order, so that the most recent post appears first, at the top of the web page. Until 2009, blogs were usually the work of a single individual,[citation needed] occasionally of a small group, and often covered a single subject or topic. In the 2010s, "multi-author blogs" (MABs) emerged, featuring the writing of multiple authors and sometimes professionally edited. MABs from newspapers, other media outlets, universities, think tanks, advocacy groups, and similar institutions account for an increasing quantity of blog traffic. The rise of Twitter and other "microblogging" systems helps integrate MABs and single-author blogs into the news media. Blog can also be used as a verb, meaning to maintain or add content to a blog.

The emergence and growth of blogs in the late 1990s coincided with the advent of web publishing tools that facilitated the posting of content by non-technical users who did not have much experience with HTML or computer programming. Previously, a knowledge of such technologies as HTML and File Transfer Protocol had been required to publish content on the Web, and early Web users therefore tended to be hackers and computer enthusiasts. In the 2010s, the majority are interactive Web 2.0 websites, allowing visitors to leave online comments, and it is this interactivity that distinguishes them from other static websites.[2] In that sense, blogging can be seen as a form of social networking service. Indeed, bloggers not only produce content to post on their blogs but also often build social relations with their readers and other bloggers.[3] However, there are high-readership blogs which do not allow comments.

Many blogs provide commentary on a particular subject or topic, ranging from politics to sports. Others function as more personal online diaries, and others function more as online brand advertising of a particular individual or company. A typical blog combines text, digital images, and links to other blogs, web pages, and other media related to its topic. The ability of readers to leave publicly viewable comments, and interact with other commenters, is an important contribution to the popularity of many blogs. However, blog owners or authors often moderate and filter online comments to remove hate speech or other offensive content. Most blogs are primarily textual, although some focus on art (art blogs), photographs (photoblogs), videos (video blogs or "vlogs"), music (MP3 blogs), and audio (podcasts). In education, blogs can be used as instructional resources. These blogs are referred to as edublogs. Microblogging is another type of blogging, featuring very short posts.

'Blog' and 'blogging' are now loosely used for content creation and sharing on social media, especially when the content is long-form and one creates and shares content on regular basis. So, one could be maintaining a blog on Facebook or blogging on Instagram.

On February 16, 2011, there were over 156 million public blogs in existence. On February 20, 2014, there were around 172 million Tumblr[4] and 75.8 million WordPress[5] blogs in existence worldwide. According to critics and other bloggers, Blogger is the most popular blogging service used today. However, Blogger does not offer public statistics.[6][7] Technorati lists 1.3 million blogs as of February 22, 2014.[8]

ezStack.Systems
  • Get Started
  • Contact

Frequently Asked Questions

Why did you create the ezStack builder application?

I have been interested in software automation for a long time and I thought this would be a good way to try out some ideas and learn about Node.js.

Who are you?

I am a husband and a father of 3 with 25 years experience in the IT corporate world in Calgary, Canada.

What does /builder do?

ezStack builder is a web application to help non-developers create dynamic web applications. ezStack builder connects to any Linux server (via SSH) and executes scripts to add functionality. Functionality is organized in modular containers called components.

How do components help to build web servers and web apps?

A component is the information required to automatically build an asset on your target server. It contains scripts and images and html and what ever is needed to build and deploy a given functionality. A component's action can be as broad as installing a full application or it can be as specific as inserting a button color element. An end user can arrange components to create rich web applications that are unique.

What is the status of /builder code and can I download a copy of the source?

ezStack builder is currently in development. There is a repository available on Github. https://github.com/sbgh/builder

So it's basically outsystems is what I'm seeing?

Outsystems [like all sas website builders] is a proprietary platform that requires a sign-up. The end user built apps are Outsystems code. It is centrally managed and profit driven.

ezstack free open source, distributed and collaborative. It connects to other servers and builds based on the user's plan. The end user owns and can manage (via dnd) all code above the OS on the target instance.

So you're saying basically digital servers for the individual vs enterprise?

Yes, self managed digital environments for the individual. There will be components for business solutions and for personal convenience or entertainment..

ops.insert:
Provides a simple service to get jason data from a data store.
Returns a row or all rows. 
Call service with 'id=#' to get all rows. Call with 'id=[id]' to get a specific row.
Eg: 
http://myNode/ezGet&id=#
   This will return all rows
http://myNode/ezGet&id=123
  This will return only row where id=123

56c68b08-cf20-4a9a-8b08-ee6b80469433.name: Prepare the LAMP server
56c68b08-cf20-4a9a-8b08-ee6b80469433.script:
setTimeout:180000 #3min
sudo yum-complete-transaction --cleanup-only
#Update yum installer
sudo yum update -y
#Install Maria & php

sudo amazon-linux-extras install -y lamp-mariadb10.2-php7.2 php7.2

#sudo yum install -y php-gd
#sudo systemctl restart php-fpm

cat /etc/system-release

#install httpd
sudo rm -f /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf
sudo yum install -y httpd mariadb-server
sudo /home/ec2-user/bin/<%s.Replace file str with str%> 'Listen 80' 'Listen <%a.testingPort%> #listen_port_row' /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf

sudo systemctl start httpd
sudo systemctl enable httpd
sudo systemctl is-enabled httpd

sudo usermod -a -G apache ec2-user

ba44db82-1b26-4588-8d6e-34a742dccbbb.name: update apache file permissions

1a8d37c1-22c1-4d51-b55a-561b1f8fb6e7.name: install Wordpress
1a8d37c1-22c1-4d51-b55a-561b1f8fb6e7.script:
setTimeout:180000 #3min
wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz
tar -xzf latest.tar.gz

rm -f /var/www/html/<%a.wpFolder%>/wp-config.php
mkdir /var/www/html/<%a.wpFolder%>
cp -r wordpress/* /var/www/html/<%a.wpFolder%> 

cp /var/www/html/<%a.wpFolder%>/wp-config-sample.php /var/www/html/<%a.wpFolder%>/wp-config.php

#Grant file ownership of /var/www and its contents to the apache user.
sudo chown -R apache /var/www

#Grant group ownership of /var/www and its contents to the apache group.
sudo chgrp -R apache /var/www

#Change the directory permissions of /var/www and its subdirectories to add group write permissions and to set the group ID on future subdirectories.
sudo chmod 2775 /var/www
find /var/www -type d -exec sudo chmod 2775 {} \;

#Recursively change the file permissions of /var/www and its subdirectories to add group write permissions.
find /var/www -type f -exec sudo chmod 0664 {} \;

#Restart the Apache web server to pick up the new group and permissions.
sudo systemctl restart httpd

4dfb8b82-076c-47e9-8b78-0d3f93f46972.name: setup Wordpress database
4dfb8b82-076c-47e9-8b78-0d3f93f46972.script:
#mysql_secure_installation
setTimeout:360000 #6min

sudo systemctl status mariadb

sudo systemctl start mariadb

# Make sure that NOBODY can access the server without a password
sudo mysql -e "UPDATE mysql.user SET Password = PASSWORD('<%c.root-password%>') WHERE User = 'root';"

sudo systemctl restart mariadb

# Kill the anonymous users
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "DROP USER ''@'localhost';"
# Because our hostname varies we'll use some Bash magic here.
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "DROP USER ''@'$(hostname)';"
# Kill off the demo database
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "DROP DATABASE test;"

# create user
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "DROP USER '<%c.wordpress-user%>'@'localhost';"
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "CREATE USER '<%c.wordpress-user%>'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY '<%c.user-password%>';"

# create user db
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "DROP DATABASE <%c.DatabaseName%>;"
sudo mysqladmin -u root -p<%c.root-password%> create <%c.DatabaseName%> 

#GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON <%c.DatabaseName%> . * TO '<%c.wordpress-user%>'@'localhost';"

# Make our changes take effect
sudo mysql -p<%c.root-password%> -e "FLUSH PRIVILEGES;"


cd /var/www/html/<%a.wpFolder%>

#sudo cp wp-config-sample.php wp-config.php

# Update wp-config.php
sudo /home/ec2-user/bin/<%s.Replace file str with str%> 'database_name_here' <%c.DatabaseName%> wp-config.php
sudo /home/ec2-user/bin/<%s.Replace file str with str%> 'username_here' <%c.wordpress-user%> wp-config.php
sudo /home/ec2-user/bin/<%s.Replace file str with str%> 'password_here' <%c.user-password%> wp-config.php
sudo /home/ec2-user/bin/<%s.Replace file str with str%> 'put your unique phrase here' <%c.salt%> wp-config.php
